Saturday, February 10, 2024

driving from Fairfield to Lake Shawnee campground in Kansas.

Taking 34 out of Fairfield to Oseola then south on 35. We are being diverted to 5 south out of Albia. by google to save 5 minutes time. Taking us to J18 to S70. Road is a bit bumpy.

County south 70 . Just saw a coyote. 68 miles from Fairfield to bridge view at Lake Rathbun.

Road is pretty empty, little traffic. Nice road. Turn right J18.really bumpy!!!Then turn left onto S56. Pretty good North wind 15-20 mph.

Still very bumpy. The road is quite narrow. Turn right onto 2West. There are too many turns for our camper. Next time we will go straight to 35 from 34. 2West is not as bumpy but still bumpy. Typical Iowa landscape, rolling hills. Some forested areas mostly farm land. Saw a hawk in the middle of the highway feeding. Just continued to eat as cars past on either side.

Probably best road is county 2 from 35 straight to centerville, then county 5 to alba. Above route a little more scenic, but about 6 turns and some narrow and slightly bumpy roads.

Finished picking up house and packing in morning. Left driveway 1015 and town 1030. Erin packed lunch for us and helped getting things out to trailer and recycle/garbage.

15-20mph wind from n/nw. Getting about 9.2mpg so far.

120 miles to i35 south still 9.2pmg, should get nice wind boost now 1:00pm

310 to Lake Shawnee camp. Very nice stopover place. Camp is on a small lake on edge of Topeka.

 

Sunday, February 11, 2024

Camp Gunsmoke

Easy little day’s travel to Dodge City, 280 miles. Only one near death experience with a near miss of a semi doing 75mph as we came down the on ramp at about 50. Driver (not to be named to protect the guilty) upset that the semi did not yield the obvious right of way to the on ramp.

 

Interstate 70 a little rough today, was great yesterday from KC to Topeka, but that was tollway. State roads and US56 from 70 to Dodge City were good. Gunsmoke RV Park is a nice little RV site outside Dodge City. Nothing special in terms of scenery. We decided to splurge to stay here and get their wifi for watching the Super Bowl. The wifi worked great. Currently 49ers up 10 - 3 midway through 3rd.

 

Was also super convenient to have full hookup, and level pullthrough site. No need to unhook anything. Should be able to pull out quickly in morning. Low of 24 tonight so decided to just fill up about 1/3 + of the freshwater tank rather than hook up to the water. This way don’t have to worry about a frozen hose in the morning, which can be a hassle even though they have heat wiring on the faucets.

Location: 37.239462, 100.628513

Monday, February 12, 2024

Valley of Fires: Not in Kansas Anymore, Dot

What time is it? Seems awfully cold in here. 4:00AM, better check the thermostat, heater should be going. 56 degrees inside, probably mid-20’s outside, no heat. Pull on jeans, find a coat, bare feet in shoes, outside to switch over to 2nd propane tank. Luckily cover comes off easily in the dark. Lefty-loosey, open the 2nd tank, tank gauge jumps to green, yay. Flip the gasoline toggle to 2nd tank, gas line gauge goes from red to green, yay. Back inside, turn off heater at thermostat, back to on, few seconds and heater fire is back on, yay. Back to nice warm bed, double yay.

 

Up about 7:30,short meditation program in bed, then morning ‘ablutions’, outside to drain black and front grey tanks. Heavy frost on everything, solid freeze. Out of Gunsmoke RV Camp by 8:30. Nice sunny cold February morning. Dodge City and western Kansas pretty similar feeling to Aberdeen with a few more feedlots and grain elevators along the road. Going via U.S. 56 and state 23 to U.S. 54. Stopped for gas at Love’s in Liberal KS. Love the 5 foot rubber window squeegees. Lots of Loves in Kansas. Our new fav gas station with the RV, even though the ‘trucks’ section is only diesel—for ‘real’ trucks.

 

11:32am, just entered Texas. Took about an hour to drive all the way through Oklahoma— panhandle. Roads have been mostly good so far, some rough spots. B/B+.

 

12:50pm (mountain time now) us54 was B+ in ks/ok and A- in Texas panhandle, C in NM. Scenery better than Texas and KS, but roads bad. Got on I40 at Tucamari, that is almost worse than us54 was from nm state line to tucamari, which was not good. Driving in passing lane a little better, but enough traffic is not great to be in passing lane.

 

Us54 through tx panhandle very flat and main feature are the huge (and smelly) feed lots.

 

1:40pm was just going to write that road is better now, then went over big 10 inch deep potholes by bridge—with large semi next to us in other lane. :-(.

A little better up to Santa Rosa. Santa Rosa seemed a nice quaint town — in contrast to what one sees of Tucamari. Might be just the road goes through the poorest part of tucamari.

 

US54 from Santa Rosa ok B-/B . Little rough still. Pretty good last 70 - 100 miles B/B+ gets very scenic as approach Corizozo

 

Arrived Valley of Fires campsite 4:45. Got the very last site (phew!). Beautiful starry clear night — Milky Way, many bright constellations, but cold, 30 degrees or less

 

Location: 37.23946, 100.62851

Tuesday, February 13, 2024

Last Leg to Green Valley

Nice night at Valley of Fires. Beautiful BLM campground and bright star sky. Got into the very last camp site (only 17 for RVs). It had water but no electricity, so last night on batteries, which were a little funky. Showed full charge when arrived, but quickly dropped off. Voltage readings drop when RV using any electricity—e.g., fan for heater. Maybe batteries getting old and weak. Victron apps probably more accurate than RV gauge, and that showed a low voltage warning—11.5V(??).

 

Up early and on road by 8:00. (Beautiful sunrise over the mountains.)

 

 

Washed truck and trailer in Deming. Nice car wash there with bays for trucks. Cost about 30 to do both (by hand). Worthwhile, the trailer was pretty dirty from last summer. Washed top as well as all sides. Got gas at Lovings just west of Las Cruces. Not a great Lovings. Pretty tight and packed and difficult to maneuver.

 

Roads decent, 10 was very nice the first 100 or so miles from Las Cruces (west of Las Cruces), then ok but a little rougher. 470 miles for the day. 11.2mpg, 11 from Valley Fires to Las Cruces, which was good considering had it in 4wd. (Put it in that night before when parking and forgot to switch back. Morale - always put things they way you want them to be before leave them, too often forget to set when return — e.g., also forgot to secure the lp tank cover the night before in Dodge City).

 

 

Location: 32.459686, 106.42263

Thursday, February 22, 2024

Off roading -- Chimney Rock

 

1 hour from GVR to Santa Catalina National Forest east of Tucson (60 miles), then 2 hours over 10 miles of pot holes, dust, and washouts up several thousand feet. Awesome views, fun to climb around Chimney Rock and the surrounding rock formations. Spectacular views on the winding road up the mountain over the surrounding valleys including all of Tucson to the west.

 

Traveled with 6 other vehicles from GVR. Very grateful to Carl (and Laura) (from Oregon) who planned out the route including driving it in advance, which takes 3 hours each way.

 

Also met Dan and Joni (?) from Grand Rapids, MI, Clem and Nancy from town south of Ann Arbor, Jim and ? From Chillicothe Mo.
